## Part 1 — API Rules

### 1. Query Chain Pattern

Every data access follows the **Query Chain** pattern. Chains are built from a
root query constructor, zero or more filters, optional relation loads, optional
ordering, **required** documentation calls, and a terminal executor.

```rust
Q::{{ entities[0].rust_module }}s()
    .{{ entities[0].attribute_predicate_prefix }}_<property>_<operator>(value)  // 0..N filters
    .select_<relation>()               // 0..N relation loads
    .order_by_<property>_asc()          // optional ordering
    .comment("what this query loads")   // REQUIRED — describes the data
    .purpose("why this data is needed") // REQUIRED — describes the intent
    .execute_for_list(&ctx).await?      // terminal — executes the query
```

**Terminal methods:**

| Method | Returns |
|--------|---------|
| `.execute_for_list(&ctx).await?` | `Vec<Entity>` — all matching rows |
| `.execute_for_first(&ctx).await?` | `Option<Entity>` — first match |
| `.execute_for_page(&ctx, page, size).await?` | paginated result |
| `.count(&ctx).await?` | `i64` — row count |

> ⚠️ Every query chain **must** include both `.comment(...)` and `.purpose(...)`.
> Omitting them is a compile-time or review-time error.

